# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitachi-rail-italy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The **A Line** (formerly and colloquially the **Blue Line**) is a light rail line in Los Angeles County, California.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Part of the Los Angeles Metro Rail system and operated by Los Angeles Metro, it is the world's longest modern light rail line at 57.7 miles (92.9 km).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A Line serves 48 stations, running east–west between Pomona and Pasadena, then north–south between Pasadena and Long Beach.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In Downtown Los Angeles it interlines with the E Line, sharing five stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Service operates about 19 hours daily with headways as short as 8 minutes during peak hours.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] It is the busiest light rail route in the system, carrying over 22 million riders in 2024 and averaging 69,216 weekday boardings in May 2024.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A Line's first segment, between the southern edge of Downtown Los Angeles and Long Beach, opened in 1990 as the inaugural line of the Metro Rail system, using much of the Pacific Electric's former Long Beach Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Plans to extend the line north through Downtown Los Angeles to Pasadena were proposed in the 1980s but delayed due to funding constraints.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Instead, the standalone Gold Line (renamed the L Line in 2020) opened in 2003 from Union Station at the northern edge of Downtown Los Angeles to Pasadena, and was extended east to Azusa in 2016.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The original plan was realized with the completion of the Regional Connector tunnel across Downtown Los Angeles in 2023, which linked the A Line to the former L Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line was extended further east to Pomona in 2025.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A Line runs 57.7 miles (92.9 km) between Pomona and Downtown Long Beach, serving 48 stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line's northern terminus is at Pomona North station in Pomona, shared with the Metrolink San Bernardino Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line briefly runs northwest, entering La Verne before stopping at La Verne/Fairplex station, located adjacent to the campus of University of La Verne.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line continues northwest, entering San Dimas before stopping at San Dimas station at San Dimas Avenue.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line continues northwest, entering Glendora and crossing underneath the SR 57 and I-210 freeways, curving through the city, before stopping at Glendora station at Vermont Avenue.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line continues northwest, curving west and entering Azusa before stopping at APU/Citrus College station just west of Citrus Avenue and north of the two universities.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line runs west through Azusa before stopping at Azusa Downtown station at Azusa Avenue, north of Foothill Boulevard.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Continuing west, the line crosses over the I-210 freeway and runs parallel to it, entering Irwindale before stopping at Irwindale station at Irwindale Avenue.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] After this station, the line continues west, crossing over the San Gabriel River and underneath the I-605 freeway, diverging from I-210 and entering Duarte, before stopping at Duarte/City of Hope station located on the north side of Duarte Road, across from the City of Hope National Medical Center.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Continuing west, the line parallels Duarte Road, entering Monrovia, before diverging northwest just before arriving at Monrovia station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Entering Arcadia, the line crosses all street crossings on bridges except for First Avenue at the at-grade Arcadia station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Continuing west, the line reconverges with and enters the median of I-210 and continues west to Sierra Madre Villa station in Pasadena.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Six stations serve different parts of Pasadena, with three of them in the freeway's median.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In Old Pasadena, the line travels underground for almost half a mile, passing under Pasadena's main thoroughfare, Colorado Boulevard, which makes the Memorial Park station below grade.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The station serves most of Pasadena's fine dining, shops, malls, and civic center.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line continues south through downtown Pasadena and South Pasadena, primarily at grade.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] North of Highland Park, the line crosses over the Arroyo Seco Parkway (State Route 110) via the Santa Fe Arroyo Seco Railroad Bridge towards Highland Park.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] After Highland Park station, the line runs in the median of Marmion Way, where trains go at only 20 miles per hour (32 km/h).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] After Avenue 50, the line runs primarily at grade in its own right of way, except for a short tunnel underneath the intersection of Figueroa Street and Pasadena Avenue.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] From here, the line continues, with a handful of stations serving the hillside areas north of downtown, including Lincoln Heights, Mount Washington, and the Southwest Museum of the American Indian.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Northeast of Chinatown, the line crosses over the Los Angeles River on an elevated viaduct.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Continuing on the elevated viaduct, the line stops at Chinatown station before arriving at Union Station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] At Union Station, passengers can transfer to the B and D rapid transit lines, Metrolink commuter rail, Amtrak, and buses.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The entire section of the line north of Union Station follows the current and former right of way of the Pasadena Subdivision, which was originally built by the Los Angeles and San Gabriel Valley Railroad between 1883 and 1887.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] South of Union Station, trains use the Regional Connector through Downtown Los Angeles.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In Little Tokyo, the line enters the new tunnel north of Temple Street to serve the replacement underground Little Tokyo/Arts District station, where the line merges with the E Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The two lines turn west to run under 2nd Street and the 2nd Street Tunnel, as well as the B and D lines, with clearances as low as 7 feet (2.1 m).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The Regional Connector tunnel connects to the north end of 7th Street/Metro Center station, the former northern terminal of the A Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line continues south along Flower Street, transitioning from underground to street level at 11th St.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Passengers can connect to the bus rapid transit J Line at 7th Street/Metro Center, Pico, and Grand/LATTC stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A and E Lines diverge at Flower Street and Washington Boulevard.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] E Line trains continue south along Flower Street, and the A Line turns east onto Washington Boulevard before turning south into the former Pacific Electric right of way at Long Beach Avenue.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] This historic rail corridor has four tracks, two for A Line trains and two for freight trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Along the corridor, there are some flyovers to either eliminate grade crossings in more densely populated areas or pass over diverging freight tracks.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Passengers can connect with the C Line at the Willowbrook/Rosa Parks station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Just south of Willow Street station, A Line trains exit the rail corridor and begin street running in the median of Long Beach Boulevard into the city of Long Beach, where trains travel through the Long Beach Transit Mall while making a loop using 1st Street, Pacific Avenue, and 8th Street.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] A Line service hours are from approximately 4:30 a.m. and 11:45 p.m. daily.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Trains operate every 8 minutes during peak hours, Monday to Friday.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Trains run every 10 minutes, during midday on weekdays and weekends, from 9:00 a.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Night and early morning service is approximately every 20 minutes every day.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The full travel time of the 57.7-mile (92.9 km) line is about 2 hours and 12 minutes, including a brief layover at Union Station for a crew change.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line's scheduled average speed is 26 miles per hour (42 km/h), with maximum speeds ranging from under 10 miles per hour (16 km/h) at surface level in Downtown Los Angeles to 55 miles per hour (89 km/h) on dedicated corridors.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Much of the initial segment of the A Line from Downtown Los Angeles to Long Beach follows the route of the Pacific Electric's Long Beach Line, which ended service in 1961.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The old route gave the new light rail trains a private right of way between Washington and Willow Street stations allowing them to reach higher speeds between stops.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line initially opened as the Blue Line on Saturday, July 14, 1990, and ran from Pico to Anaheim Street.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The Long Beach Loop section to Long Beach opened in September 1990, followed by the tunnel into 7th Street/Metro Center in February 1991.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The initial light rail segment cost US$877 million ($2.16 billion in 2025 adjusted for inflation).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The route reached full capacity after one decade of service, and from 1999 to 2001, the Blue Line underwent a US$11 million project to lengthen 19 of its platforms to accommodate three-car trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] There were also plans since the 1980s to extend the Blue Line north to Pasadena but the connection through downtown was postponed due to funding constraints from the voter-approved 1998 Proposition A.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The proposition restricted local county subway funding, halting the process of the Blue Line extension and other rail transit projects from advancing.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The Blue Line was renovated in 2019, with the southern half of the line being closed for the first five months and the northern half closing for the following five months (10 months total).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Metro provided a bus shuttle service to compensate for the lack of rail service.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Metro officially reopened the line on November 2, 2019, rebranding it as the A Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The renovation helped improve the line's speed and reliability by replacing and modernizing old tracks, signals, train control systems, and bridges.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Much of the A Line's right of way north of Union Station through the San Gabriel Valley was built by the Los Angeles and San Gabriel Valley Railroad in 1885.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] It was eventually taken over by the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway, as part of the Pasadena Subdivision, which saw Amtrak service until 1994, when construction began on the conversion to light rail.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Planners envisioned extending the existing Blue Line (A Line) north of 7th Street/Metro Center, but it was canceled due to funding shortages.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] However, the mostly above-ground segment of the extension from Union Station to Pasadena advanced and began construction in 1994 as a separate line but was suspended again by 1998 due to the Proposition A ban.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Later that year, a bill was authorized to create a new independent construction authority to finish the line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The agency, now known as the Foothill Gold Line Construction Authority, resumed light rail construction in 2000 and completed the line three years later.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The then-renamed Gold Line, between Union Station and Sierra Madre Villa station in East Pasadena, opened on July 26, 2003.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In 2016, the Gold Line was extended east from Pasadena as part of Phase 2A (Phase 1 was the initial Los Angeles to Pasadena segment) of the Foothill Extension, running between Sierra Madre Villa and APU/Citrus College stations in Azusa.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The extension was constructed by the Foothill Gold Line Construction Authority and added six new stations to the Gold Line serving the cities of Arcadia, Monrovia, Duarte, Irwindale, and Azusa.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] A groundbreaking ceremony for Phase 2A was held on June 26, 2010; construction began the following summer and was completed in September 2015, with the extension entering service on March 5, 2016.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Like other lines in the Los Angeles Metro system, the Gold Line's designation became a letter in 2020.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] This was the beginning of a process where all Metro Rail and Busway lines would be identified by a letter name rather than a system of colors.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The Gold Line was renamed to the L Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The Regional Connector Transit Project constructed a 1.9-mile (3.1 km) light rail tunnel across Downtown Los Angeles that connected A and E lines to the L Line, with the purpose of reducing transfers and travel times through downtown.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The project completed the late 1990s vision of the "Pasadena Blue Line," connecting the northern (Union Station–Azusa) segment of the L Line to the A Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] This enabled A Line trains to run from Long Beach to Azusa through the new tunnel.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The southern (Pico/Aliso–East LA) segment was combined with the existing E Line between Downtown Los Angeles and Santa Monica.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The new east-west line kept the E Line name but uses the L Line's gold color.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Two new stations were also constructed in the tunnel, providing more service to destinations and communities in Downtown Los Angeles.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Formal studies and planning for the Regional Connector began in 2004 and was approved in 2012.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] A groundbreaking ceremony was held on September 30, 2014, marking the start of major construction.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] To accommodate the new tunnel, the existing at-grade L Line Little Tokyo/Arts District station was demolished in 2020 and rebuilt as a subway station approximately 500 feet (150 m) south and on the opposite side of Alameda Street from its former location.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Starting on April 9, 2023, the A, E, and L Line trains ran through the Regional Connector tunnel for final testing.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The project officially opened for revenue service on June 16, 2023.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Once the Regional Connector was completed, the alignment of the L Line was split into two parts at Little Tokyo/Arts District station, with the portion north of the station joined to the A Line, extending it to connect Long Beach with Azusa.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] With this change, the A Line officially became the longest, modern day light rail line in the world.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The alignment east of Little Tokyo/Arts District station was assigned to the E Line, extending it to connect Santa Monica and East Los Angeles directly.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] At this time, the L Line ceased to exist as a separate line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The first part of Phase 2B of the Foothill Extension, running between APU/Citrus College station in Azusa and Pomona North station in Pomona, opened on September 19, 2025.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] This section, like the original Gold Line to Pasadena, and Phase 2A of the Foothill Extension, was built by the Foothill Gold Line Construction Authority (Foothill Gold Line).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The second part of the Foothill Extension Phase 2B project will further extend the A Line east to the Claremont San Bernardino Line station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Construction is expected to break ground in 2027 and be completed in 2031.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The **Southeast Gateway Line** is a planned light rail line, mostly following the Pacific Electric's historic West Santa Ana Branch, connecting Downtown Los Angeles to the city of Artesia, along with other cities in southeastern Los Angeles County.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] It will link the southeast/Gateway cities with the A Line at Slauson station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Construction is planned to begin in 2025 with service starting in 2035.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Metro estimates it will take 10 years to build.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A Line often operates at capacity, and various options to increase capacity have been considered, such as four-car or more frequent trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Both have problems: it would be difficult or impossible to lengthen some of the station platforms, and the number of trains already causes delays for other vehicles at level crossings.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Since the opening of the Regional Connector, ridership on the A Line continues to increase, potentially resulting in even more capacity problems.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] One of the biggest constraints on the capacity of the A and E lines is the at-grade section along Flower Street in Downtown Los Angeles, especially Pico Station and the wye junction at Flower and Washington.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Pico Station serves both lines and cannot be bypassed, so service on both lines is limited by the capacity of the station and the grade crossing of Pico Boulevard immediately adjacent to it.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The wye junction at Flower and Washington is a similar bottleneck, as trains on both lines must cross a busy intersection and freeway onramp at-grade.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Accidents, gridlocked traffic, and signal delays at the junction can cause cascading service disruptions across both lines.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Various grade separation projects have been considered to improve capacity and resolve the issues with this section of track.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Over 120 motorists and pedestrians have been killed at A Line level crossings since 1990.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] There have been more than 800 collisions, making the line easily the country's deadliest and most collision-prone rail line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In 1998, the MTA commissioned Booz Allen Hamilton, Inc. to evaluate the cause of Blue Line collisions and recommend affordable solutions.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Due to this, Metro started in the early 2000s to install four-quadrant gates at crossings where the A Line shares the right of way with freight rail between Willowbrook station and Artesia station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The gates prevent drivers from going around lowered gates.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Metro also improved the safety of the A Line's pedestrian crossings by 2018.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] On Metro Rail's internal timetables, the A Line is called line **801**.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Because of the length of the line, operators do not take trains from end to end, swapping out at Union Station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Trains are operated between Pomona and Union Station by employees based at Division 24 in Monrovia.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Between Long Beach and Union Station, operators are based out of Division 11 in Rancho Dominguez.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A Line is operated out of two divisions, Metro's term for train maintenance and storage facilities.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Division 11 is located at 4350 East 208th Street in Cota, North Long Beach between Del Amo and Wardlow stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The facility can house and maintain 86 light rail vehicles and can perform heavy maintenance including repainting.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Trains get to this yard via a wye junction on the southbound tracks.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Northbound trains can enter and exit the yard via the cross tracks on the north and south sides of the junction.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Division 24 is located south of the I-210 freeway in Monrovia between Monrovia and Duarte/City of Hope stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Just like Division 11, trains access the yard via the westbound/southbound tracks from either direction of its wye junction.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] Crossovers from the eastbound track to the yard junction are located near the California Avenue and Mountain Avenue railroad crossings.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The A Line operates trains with three light rail vehicles on weekdays and two on weekends.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The line currently uses three different types of light rail vehicles: the Kinki Sharyo P3010, the Siemens P2000, and the AnsaldoBreda P2550, but has seen every type of light rail rolling stock on Metro's roster throughout its history of operation.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] When the A Line, then known as the Blue Line, first opened in 1990, the line had 54 Nippon Sharyo P865 light rail vehicles, numbered 100–153.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] These cars wore a unique livery of several blue stripes and a single red stripe, reflecting the Blue Line's color designation and its Pacific Electric Red Car heritage.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In 2000, Metro transferred all 15 Nippon Sharyo P2020 (numbered 154-168) light rail vehicles from the Green Line (now the C Line) to the Blue Line fleet.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] These light rail vehicles were nearly identical to the older P865 model but were about five years newer and originally had equipment for automatic train operation.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In 2012, Metro transferred some Siemens P2000 light rail vehicles from the Gold Line to the A (then Blue) Line fleet.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] These vehicles were used before their refurbishment.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] As of 2023, some are currently being tested on the A Line, and they made a rocky return to the A Line in late 2024.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In 2017, the Blue Line received 78 Kinki Sharyo P3010 light rail vehicles, the first new cars for the line since it opened in 1990.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] As the P3010 fleet was introduced, Metro gradually retired all of the remaining P865 light rail vehicles, followed by the P2020 fleet.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] In 2023, the AnsaldoBreda P2550 light rail vehicles began service on the A Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/a-line-los-angeles-metro] The P2550 trains were tested on the Blue Line in 2009, but were instead assigned to the Gold Line due to weight restrictions.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The name *Ankaray* is a portmanteau of the words *Ankara* and *ray* (rail).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Plans to construct a medium-capacity rapid transit line were included in the City of Ankara's 1990 investment plan.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The planned line was reviewed jointly by the Undersecretariat of the Treasury, State Planning Organization, Ministry of Transport and EGO and was approved in late 1991.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The line was planned to begin in Söğütözü and run east to Dikimevi, through Kızılay.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] At Kızılay, transfer to the under construction M1 line to Batıkent would be possible.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Further eastward extension into Mamak was also considered but never approved.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Construction of the line began on 7 April 1992 and was completed in 1996.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The opening of Ankaray took place on 30 August 1996 in a ceremony in which Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan inaugurated the line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Ankaray became the second rapid transit line in Turkey, after the M1 line in Istanbul and ahead of the M1 line of the Ankara Metro (1997) and the Bornova—Üçyol Line of the İzmir Metro (2000).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Ankaray runs along a 8.527 km (5.298 mi) mostly east-west route from the Ankara Intercity Coach Terminal in Söğütözü to Dikimevi in northeast Çankaya, consisting of 11 stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The majority of the route is underground, with the exception being the westernmost 0.74 km (0.46 mi) portion of the line between AŞTİ and Emek stations.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The route begins at AŞTİ, with the station located on the east side of Mevlana Boulevard, across from the Coach Terminal.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The route runs within an embankment to Emek, then heads underground about 254 m (833 ft) north of the station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The route turns east at Bahriye Üçok Avenue and continues under the Avenue, which becomes Gazi Mustafa Kemal Boulevard near Anıtkabir.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] At Maltepe station, an out-of-system connection to the Ankara railway station is available.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The line continues east reaching Kızılay, where transfer to M1 and M2 lines are available.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] After Kızılay the Ankaray route continues under Ziya Gökalp Avenue, until Kurtuluş.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] At Kurtuluş, transfer to commuter rail service is available.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] From Kurtuluş the route continues under Cemal Gürsel Avenue until reaching its eastern terminus, Dikimevi.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Like all mass transit in the Ankara area, Ankaray uses the Ankarakart smartcard system.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The entire route is within the same fare zone.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The cost of a single ride, using the Ankarakart, costs ₺2.50 ($0.67, as of 2018) for a full fare, while a reduced fare ride costs ₺1.75 ($0.47).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] A non-Ankarakart single ticket costs ₺4 ($1.07).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Transferring to Ankaray via another metro line or bus costs ₺1 ($0.27) for full fare and ₺0.25 ($0.07) for reduced fare riders.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] (*) Starred transfers are under construction.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Ankaray uses different rolling stock than the rest of the Ankara Metro system.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Built jointly by AEG and Siemens, they were ordered by the Ankara Municipality in January 1992 and delivered shortly before the opening of the line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] A total of 33 cars were built and delivered for the line; 22 with an operator's cabin and 11 without.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Trains draw power via third rail, which is electrified at 750 V DC.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Ankaray trains usually operate with a total of six cars (3 married pairs).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Each married pair of cars has a length of 29 m (95 ft) and a width of 2.65 m (8 ft 8 in).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] All Ankaray rolling stock is stored and maintained at the Söğütözü Maintenance Facility in Yenimahalle.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] Expansion of the Ankaray line from AŞTİ to Söğütözü was approved on 25 April 2011 and construction began in September 2012.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The short 0.8 km (0.50 mi) southwest expansion would meet the M2 line at Söğütözü station.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] The tunnel and station was completed in early 2014, along with the opening of the M2 line from Kızılay to Koru.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ankaray] However, the line has not yet been put into service for reasons unclear.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] The **900 Series**, nicknamed and commonly known as "**Meneghino"** is an electric multiple unit manufactured by Italian companies **Firema** and **AnsaldoBreda,** designed for the Milan Metro.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] Its nickname means *of Milan* in Italian.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] The trains are made up of 6 permanently coupled coaches, comprising two identical traction units at each end, with a total length of about 105 m (344 ft 6 in).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] Each Traction Unit consists of two identical motor cars and a trailer with the driver's cab.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] The traction voltage can be 750 V or 1500 V to comply with the different voltages and feeding systems in use on Milan Metro lines (fourth rail on M1, catenary on M2 and M3).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] Trains have a total of 24 doors per side and are equipped with surveillance cameras and LCD screens.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] The train began to replace the old Milan Metro trains in March 2009 on lines 1 and 2, as well as supplement the rolling stock on line 3.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda-meneghino] It is not used on lines 4 or 5, which use smaller-sized driverless trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] As of April 1, 2021, the company was merged into Hitachi Rail STS.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Ansaldo & C.* was registered in Genoa as a manufacturer of steam locomotives, rail rolling stock and steam engines.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The company was backed by Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, the powerful finance minister of Piedmont-Sardinia, who aimed to reduce its dependence on imported trains and rolling stock.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Ansaldo entered the age of the steam locomotive in 1854 with its model FS113, also known as *Sampierdarena*.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] During the First World War, Ansaldo became a large supplier of weapons to the Italian army; facing insurmountable difficulties with post-war reconversion to civilian industry, the company was eventually nationalised in 1921.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] During the rest of the 1900s, the company diversified in different fields, especially power generation (Ansaldo Energia) and nuclear research, while the rolling stock activities were reunited under Ansaldo Trasporti.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In 1886, Ernesto Breda founded in Milan *Società Italiana Ernesto Breda*.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] By 1908, Breda's thousandth locomotive was built.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Breda entered the electric locomotive era in 1936 with the production of the FS Class ETR 200 series electric multiple unit.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In 1939 this type set the land speed record for rail vehicles at 203 km/h (126 mph).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Similarly to Ansaldo, also Breda became a main weapon supplier to the Fascist regime, especially of artillery and airplanes.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] After the Second World War the company was facing bankruptcy, and was eventually nationalised in 1947.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] During the Italian economic miracle of the 1950-60s, Breda produced a highly successful commuter train, the FS Class ETR 300, several classes of railcars and locomotives, and diversified into defense (OTO Melara) and, especially, buses.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In the 1980s Breda participated in the consortium that designed the first Italian high-speed train, the FS Class ETR 500.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In a massive restructuring effort, in 2001 the Italian state merged all the rolling stock activities of the then loss-making Ansaldo and Breda in a new company, *AnsaldoBreda*, that in turn became part of the Finmeccanica state-owned group.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The new company won a string of big contracts across Europe and the United States; however, lacking adequate funding and capacity, AnsaldoBreda became infamous for its unreliable products and long delays, damaging the reputation of the company.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In 1991, 100 4000 Series railcars from AnsaldoBreda were delivered to the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] On 4 July 2010, after several incidents where the doors would open while the train was in motion, Metro removed the fleet for repairs until 20 July that year.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] On 17 November 2016 Metro discovered an error in which a 4000-series car would display an incorrect speed limit to a train operator while in manual mode (which is the only mode used since the June 2009 Washington Metro train collision).
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] On 7 June 2017 Metro announced that the 4000-series cars would be fully retired and removed from service on 1 July 2017, and by that date all cars were taken out of service.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Delivery of 83 IC4 AnsaldoBreda trainsets for the Danish State Railways DSB was originally planned for 2003–2006.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] However, the last train was delivered only in 2013 and IC4 trains have seen many technical problems during their service.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] DSB announced in 2016 that the trains would be withdrawn from service from 2024.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] After winning a big contract for the Dutch-Belgium Fyra project in 2004, nine V250 train units were delivered to the Dutch partner NS over five years later than originally contracted.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Soon after the trains went into service on the high-speed line between the Netherlands and Belgium, the V250 suffered a number of severe technical problems.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The Fyra had a poor reputation for reliability.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] After a month of operations more than 5% of all trains were cancelled and less than 45% of them ran on schedule.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] On 31 May 2013, the Belgium partner NMBS/SNCB announced that they would exit the Fyra project and cancel the contract with AnsaldoBreda.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The City of Gothenburg in Sweden has ordered 40 one-directional Sirio trams which were to be put into service on the Gothenburg tram network during 2005 and onwards.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The trams were delivered late and functioned poorly when put into traffic.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Among reported problems were corrosion, excessive track damage caused by the trams, malfunctioning air conditioners inside the trams and poor ride quality.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The City of Gothenburg therefore withheld a large part of the payment for a delivered tram until fully operational.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The 32 two-directional trams delivered for the Oslo Tramway from 1999, called SL95, have met several difficulties with rust during snowy weather and the heavy weight necessitates much maintenance to streets and tracks, which make the trams expensive to operate.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] They are also considered to create more noise than necessary.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The replacement of the trams will start in 2020 and the last trams will be taken out of service in 2024.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] After 7 years on a 4-year project the region of Stockholm decided to cancel the contract on new signal system for the red metro line in Stockholm with Ansaldo on 1 billion SEK.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The prepayment of hundreds of million SEK is currently up in arbitration court.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The maintenance issues experienced by MBTA AnsaldoBreda Type 8 Vehicles delayed the retirement of the Boeing LRVs by several years.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] According to MBTA Chief Operating Officer Jeff Gonneville, they present a "maintenance challenge".
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In October 2016, the *Boston Globe* reported that the MBTA Green Line had the most derailments in the nation due to the Type 8.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] In spite of its overall terminal crisis, AnsaldoBreda managed to successfully participate in the Italian high-speed trains program until the very end of its existence.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The ETR 500, that entered service in 1993, was continuously upgraded and ran at a record speed of 362 km/h (225 mph) in the Monte Bibele tunnel between Florence and Bologna in 2009, setting a speed record for trains in a tunnel.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] A new generation high-speed train, the Frecciarossa 1000, was developed in a consortium with Bombardier Transportation and entered service in 2015.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] On 26 February 2016, a Frecciarossa 1000 reportedly attained a peak speed of 393.8 km/h (244.7 mph) while traversing the Torino-Milano high speed line.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Lacking the funds for a proper restructuring of its troubled subsidiary, Finmeccanica announced on 2 November 2015 the 'closing of transactions' covering the purchase of AnsaldoBreda by Hitachi, together with Finmeccanica's 40% stake in Ansaldo STS, for $2.2 billion.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Under the agreements signed on 24 February 2015, following a dividend distribution announced on 6 March, the purchase price for Finmeccanica's stake in Ansaldo STS has been set at €9.50 per share, amounting to a total of €761m.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] The total net consideration to be paid for AnsaldoBreda as a going concern, including property assets, amounts to around €30m.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] As a part of the deal Finmeccanica would keep the responsibility for some residual contracts.
[src:hitachi-rail-italy/ansaldobreda] Since being acquired by Hitachi, production of some British Rail Class 802 was shifted to Hitachi Rail Italy's Pistoia plant due to Hitachi Rail's Newton Aycliffe plant being at capacity.
